**What is an XSS Payload?**
==========================

A Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) payload is a malicious piece of code injected into a web application, typically through user input or other vulnerabilities. The goal of an XSS payload is to execute arbitrary JavaScript code on the client-side, allowing attackers to steal sensitive information, hijack user sessions, or take control of the victim's browser.

**Example of an XSS Payload**
```javascript
<script>alert('XSS')</script>
```
This simple payload will display a pop-up alert box when executed. More sophisticated payloads can be used to steal cookies, inject malware, or even create a backdoor into the application.

